  "definitions": {
    "d-label": {
      "type": "elementHeading",
      "level": 6,
      "text": "DISCUSSION — THREE MECHANISMS",
      "align": "left",
      "width": "hug",
      "height": "hug",
      "marginBottom": "0.5rem"
    },
    "d-simultaneous": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### Simultaneous Contrast\n\nFirst described by Chevreul in 1839, simultaneous contrast is the perceptual effect in which the same hue appears lighter against a dark ground and darker against a light one.\n\n**Design consequence:** Brand colors specified as exact hex values will not produce consistent perceptual results across dark and light UI modes. Separate palette specifications — or relative lightness tokens — are necessary for perceptual consistency.",
      "level": 4,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "slideUp",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.4,
            "delay": 0
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "d-luminance": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### Luminance Relativity\n\nContrast ratio is a ratio, not an absolute value. A 4.5:1 contrast that meets WCAG AA on a white background may produce a very different perceptual experience on a mid-tone background.\n\n**Design consequence:** Accessibility calculations must account for the background's actual luminance, not just the nominal contrast ratio. Dynamic surfaces require dynamic contrast checking.",
      "level": 4,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "slideUp",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.4,
            "delay": 0.08
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "d-cultural": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### Cultural Framing\n\nRed means stop in traffic, danger in UI, luck in China, mourning in some parts of Africa. There is no universal color-emotion mapping.\n\n**Design consequence:** Color choices for global audiences should be validated with local research. Cultural color associations should be considered alongside universal perceptual ones — but should not be allowed to override accessibility requirements.",
      "level": 4,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "slideUp",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.4,
            "delay": 0.16
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
